{
  "text": "Our results also provide guidance in understanding when a particular mortality mechanism may not be adequately captured by growth rate. Although this study was largely phenomenological, we can still make biologically informed observations about why different species showed different sensitivity to spatial indices. For instance, indices designed to reflect resource competition improved mortality models for the smaller individuals of shade-tolerant species such as A. concolor and to a lesser extent C. decurrens. As shade-tolerant trees [CITATION_1] , both species can persist in subcanopy environments and presumably survive long periods of slow growth, perhaps resulting in less predictive power for growth rate in the most extreme conditions. Put simply, in very competitive environments growth rate may level off to some minimum, but increased competition would still affect resource availability and therefore likelihood of mortality.",
